SIMPLE: squid
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Squid
<hw>Squid</hw> <pr>(skw⟦icr⟧d)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf.
<er>Squirt</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Any one of
numerous species of ten-armed cephalopods having a long, tapered body,
and a caudal fin on each side; especially, any species of
<gen>Loligo</gen>, <gen>Ommastrephes</gen>, and related genera. See
<er>Calamary</er>, <er>Decacerata</er>, <er>Dibranchiata</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ Some of these squids are very abundant on the Atlantic
coast of North America, and are used in large quantities for bait,
especially in the cod fishery. The most abundant of the American squids
are the northern squid (<spn>Ommastrephes illecebrosus</spn>), ranging
from Southern New England to Newfoundland, and the southern squid
(<spn>Loligo Pealii</spn>), ranging from Virginia to
Massachusetts.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A fishhook with a piece of bright lead, bone, or
other substance, fastened on its shank to imitate a squid.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>Flying squid</b></col>, <col><b>Giant
squid</b></col></mcol>. <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <cd>See under
<er>Flying</er>, and <er>Giant</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Squid
hound</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>the striped bass.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Squier</ent>⟦br⟧
